This is particularly apparent in situations where women seek to divorce or caregivers seek alternative care for their children due to illness or economic reasons. Factors for conflict include a lack of mixed parent role modelling and separation of siblings in different orphanages, this makes for doubt and confusion when caring for children and difficulties with open access to children in the orphanages.
Many adoptive mothers from other countries have less negative ideas and attitudes, indeed the tendency for fathers to abandon families is reversed overseas where it is the women who prefer custody over jobs. In Bolivia, where men rarely apply for custody, women’s movement was more associated with their failure to secure full custody of their children post-divorce.10 These findings are in line with the discourse of the guardian politicians who champion women’s rights.
Working with the administration Bolivia is a large departmental district with significant urban and rural population. The administrative structures at trip layers were examined – local, regional and national. The study did find a high level of bureaucracy, the separation of powers between different organs of administration and political party colouring were all too apparent but when contrasting this with the better functioning and more holistic administration within infant orphanages it was found that overall administrative governance and structure is effective and less complex at the local level.
